Abstract

Context of problem: The political debate over how much to spend on military funding grows more heated as President Trump plans to increase the defense budget. This essay seeks to determine effects that military expenditures may have on life expectancy. We hypothesize that increases in military expenditures correspond to decreases in life expectancy and find that there is a statistically significant negative relationship between life expectancy and military expenditures. Using r studio, we run exploratory analysis of our data and regressions of life expectancy, military expenditures, GDP, healthcare expenditures, adults with HIV, and mean years in school for women and men. We conduct tests for significance, heteroskedasticity, correlation, and autocorrelation to determine the accuracy and value of our results. The data is compiled from Gapminder and cleaned in r studio.

Research Question and Hypothesis

In this paper we seek to consider the relationship between life expectancy and military expenditures. How does a countrys life expectancy change based on their military expenditure? The additional consideration of GDP, mean years in school, and healthcare expenditures allows one to more exactly estimate the effect of military expenditure on life expectancy. We hypothesize that increases in military expenditures correspond to decreases in life expectancy. We are aware of the positive relationship between increased GDP and increased life expectancy and we know that an increase in military expenditure does not increase GDP. Thus, we believe that an increase in military expenditure would not increase life expectancy. Additionally, an increased military expenditure could suggest that the country is experiencing more war and violence, therefore resulting in a higher mortality rate and decreasing their life expectancy.

Theory

According to the Keynesian model, increases in government spending increases GDP and serves as a pillar of support during financial crisis. However, government spending towards military has a smaller multiplier effect than spending directly into infrastructure, unemployment benefits, and education. Therefore, the benefits to GDP are mitigated. GDP is positively related to life expectancy, consequently the inefficiency of investing government spending on military funding creates a negative relationship between military spending and life expectancy.

Previous Work

The relationship between military expenditure and life expectancy has not been heavily studied. However, by understanding the relationship between life expectancy and GDP and between GDP and military expenditure, we can hypothesize the relationship between life expectancy and military expenditure. Kentor and Kick (2008) examine the effect that military expenditures per soldier have on per capita GDP growth in a variety of countries. They find that military expenditures inhibit the growth of per capita GDP, and that the effect is more pronounced in less developed countries. Additionally, the labor force expansion is slowed and the available investment capital goes towards the military rather than more productive economic opportunities. Mahumud et al. (2013) provide evidence to suggest that an increase in GDP is correlated with an increase in life expectancy. Therefore, the decrease in GDP growth seen in Kentor and Kick (2008) due to increased military expenditure could cause decreases in life expectancy.

Kentor and Jorgenson (2017) examined the effect that increased military expenditures in high-tech, capital-intensive armaments had on the under- five mortality rate and life expectancy. This study uses cross-national panel models to determine that increases in military expenditures increase the under-five mortality rate and decreases life expectancy. The study cites potential reasons for a decrease in life expectancy being that this increase in expenditure decreases the number and type of soldiers able to take advantage of health-related resources and increases income inequality.

Data description/Visualization

Our Data set consisted of 2,403 observations on 9 quantitative variables and 2 categorical variables: country (The country in question), continent (the continent to which a country belongs), year (the year to which the data applied), militaryexpenditures (the % of GDP a country spends on their military), lifeExp (average life expectancy in years), GDPpercap (GDP per capita in US dollars), GDP (GDP in billions of US dollars), HIV (the number of deaths due to HIV), healthcare (per capita total expenditure on health in US dollars), womenEd (the mean number of years spent in school for women over the age of 25), and menEd (the mean number of years spent in school for men over the age of 25). A summary of all the quantitative variables can be seen in Table 1.

Figures 14 through 20 show plots of every variable against life expectancy. All of the variables other than HIV and Military Expenditures appeared to have definite associations with Life Expectancy, as the plot for log(HIV) appeared problematic, we decided to test whether or not there was any association between a countrys military expenditures and their mean life expectancy.

Econometric Model and Basic Results

To begin constructing our model we created a model excluding the variables GDPpercapita, HIV, and womensEd due to problems with multicollinearity and normality (for explanation see Appendix part: Model selection) and conducted a Hausman test in order to see whether it was necessary for us to model our data using a fixed effects model accounting for country as a factor or whether a pooled model would be sufficient. The results are shown in Tables 2 and 3.

We found that with a p-value of \(5.2*10^{-17}\) we can safely conclude that a pooled model would be insufficient. Therefore, we arrived at the fixed effects model: \(lifeExp = \beta_0 + \beta_1factor(country) + \beta_2log(militaryExp)+\beta_3log(GDP)+\beta_4log(healthcare)+menEd\)).

We remained confident in this model despite its markedly high VIF statistics (Table 5) because of low VIF values between all the explanatory variables in a pooled version of the same model (Table 4). Given this we surmised the increase in the VIF statistics was due to the expected collinear relationship between the factor variable and all the other variables. Moreover, We chose to treat data point 737 as a potential outlier and remove it from our model because of its significant Cooks distance (Figure 21).

Our final fixed effects model showed that all else held constant, a 1% increase in a countrys military expenditures was associated with a 0.623 year drop in that countrys mean life expectancy, with a standard error of 0.136 that implies our coefficient is significantly different from 0 (over . Moreover, all else held constant at 0 the average life expectancy in each country is 38.0 years \(+\) whatever \(\beta_1factor(country)\) is for each country (can be seen in Appendix Table 1). Moreover, if we were to repeat this experiment over and over then we would expect that 99% percent of confidence intervals constructed this way would contain the true mean coefficient of log(militaryexpenditures). Finally, we found that our model explained 32.0% of the variation in Y.

Our Residuals plot of the new model showed strong evidence of heteroskedasticity.

Robustness

Given the apparent heteroskedasticity in our fixed model we conducted a Breusch-Pagan tests for heteroskedasticity which gave us a p-value of \(2.2*10^{-16}\) indicating significant heteroskedasticity in our model


    studentized Breusch-Pagan test

data:  projFN.lm
BP = 1076.4, df = 150, p-value < 2.2e-16

Given the apparent heteroskedasticity in our model we compared our fixed effects models standard errors to the robust standard errors and OLS standard errors in order to see whether or not we needed to adjust our standard errors to account for heteroskedasticity. We found that we did not need to adjust our standard errors because they were fairly similar to one another and did not influence the significance of the model.

Limitations & Future Work

Our model is far from perfect. These variables that we use cannot fully explain the changes we see in life expectancy across countries. We fail to account for the different types of military expenditure, such as technology or wages, as different countries could be allocating their expenditure differently. We also fail to account for countries that are at war. A country that goes to war will increase their military spending and we would expect a country at war to have a lower life expectancy than their norm. This is likely pushing our coefficient on military spending to be more negative. Additionally, as we use military expenditure as a percentage of GDP, a country with a small GDP at war or with its neighbors at war will have a significantly inflated military expenditure. There may also be more advanced models that we failed to consider when analyzing our data. We also fail to take into account inter-country relationships that may skew the data.

If we were to conduct further research on this subject, there are a variety of ideas and variables that it would valuable to consider. Adding utility to the model could help us understand whether military expenditures affected the countries in ways other than life expectancy. It would also be interesting to consider how the model changes when a country is at peace versus actively at war, and how the mortality rate for men aged 18 to 30 changes with both war and increased military expenditure. Considering intra-country violence and crime could allow us to consider how much of a countrys military efforts are focused within its own borders. A comparison of per soldier and per capita or per civilian expenditure might also enable us to determine how much of expenditures pay wages. This could also allow an interesting comparison of wage expenditure versus technological expenditure. Including a dummy variable for first and third world countries could also create an interesting relationship between the amount that a country spend on military and their level of development. These variables would allow us to create a more precise model of what parts of military expenditure affect life expectancy and how countries could use this data to further growth.

We decided to exclude HIV death rates from our model in favor of healthcare expenditures due to the skewed nature of the HIV data, whether logged or unlogged. We excluded the GDP Per Capita variable in favor of GDP due GDP Per Capitas high VIF value (Table 4) and excluded Womens Education in favor of Mens education because of high multicollinearity between the two (Table 4) and because Mens education appeared to be more normally distributed (Figure 12).

We arrived at the final pooled model( Model 1:\(lifeExp = \beta_1 + \beta_2log(militaryExp)+\beta_3log(GDP)+\beta_4log(healthcare)+menEd\) ) Moreover, we chose not to remove any potential outliers from our model as the edited model showed just as many, if not more outliers after being edited, and any continued effort to remove potential outliers could negatively effect our data.

After examining the plots of our pooled model we saw that there was enough variation in the model from continent to continent to justify creating a fixed effects model using country as our influence factor. We chose to use a generalized linear model factoring for country rather than a paneled linear model because, while both models presented us with the same results, the generalized linear model allowed us to more easily present our results graphically.
